Read some idiot pakistani's comment: "They have been stealing our music (lyrics) for so long. They real author or composers should be compensated".

1. These lyrics were written by Khurou  or his disciples more than 500 years ago,so no copy rights.
2. They were composed in Hindustan. Pakistan did not exist then. SO if anybody it is India which can claim the cultural copyright to it. You people anyway consider yourselves Arabs. Go and sing whatever the Arabs sing. Oh sorry!! i forgot that music is BANNED there :D

snippet.textDisplay:
The lyrics of "Chaap Tilak" are not of this world. Written by the none other than the Sufi saint of the highest order, Amir Khusrow's divine inspiration shines with full radiance in this composition. The most beautiful thing in the world is to become no-thing, which is the complete annihilation of ego. Only you exist, my beloved master, there is no more of me. My lord,  I have totally dissolved into you, and all it took was one intoxicating glance from you! 

How delicate is the love, reverence and gratitude a true disciple holds in his heart towards his spiritual master. Can it be expressed in any better way than the obeisance Khusrow’s pays to his guru Nizamuddin Auliya in this song?Indeed, the highest spiritual teachings are condensed into this beautiful song. Abida Parveen & Rahat Fateh Ali Khan are exceptionally gifted Qawwals - their masterful performance touches the soul each time, and as I listen in awe,  atleast momentarily, this little I too ceases to exist.
